  "text": "The Kubernetes watch event delivery path spans three repositories and multiple hops:\n\n**Hop 1 — etcd MVCC Store (etcd-io/etcd)**\n\n- `server/mvcc/watchable_store.go`: The `watchableStore` struct is the core MVCC store that implements the `watchable` interface. When a key-value mutation occurs, it generates `mvccpb.Event` objects and notifies all registered watchers.\n\n- `server/mvcc/watcher.go`: Defines the `WatchStream` interface and its concrete implementation `watchStream`. The `watchStream` holds a collection of `watcher` objects that share a single channel (`chan WatchResponse`) for sending watch events out of the MVCC layer. Kubernetes apiserver connects to etcd and creates a `WatchStream` via `watchableStore.NewWatchStream()`.\n\n**Hop 2 — etcd gRPC Watch Server (etcd-io/etcd)**\n\n- `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/watch.go`: The `serverWatchStream` struct bridges the MVCC `watchStream` to the gRPC `Watch_WatchServer` protocol. It holds both a `gRPCStream` (the outbound gRPC stream to the client) and a `watchStream` (the MVCC-level stream). It runs goroutines to receive events from the MVCC layer and forward them as `WatchResponse` protobuf messages over gRPC to the Kubernetes apiserver.\n\n**Hop 3 — Kubernetes API Server Watch Cache (kubernetes/kubernetes)**\n\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/cacher.go`: The `Cacher` struct is the top-level watch cache implementation. It wraps the underlying etcd storage and maintains an internal `reflector` that watches etcd via the etcd client. It runs `dispatchEvents()` to fan out incoming events to all registered `cacheWatcher` instances.\n\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/watch_cache.go`: The `watchCache` struct is an in-memory ring buffer of `watchCacheEvent` objects. It stores recent watch events and the current object state, allowing the `Cacher` to serve watch requests from cache without hitting etcd for every client.\n\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/cache_watcher.go`: The `cacheWatcher` struct represents a single watch connection from a Kubernetes client to the apiserver. It receives `watchCacheEvent` objects via its `input` channel and converts/sends them as `watch.Event` objects on its `result` channel, which is exposed to the HTTP watch handler.\n\n**Hop 4 — Kubernetes Client-Side Reflector (kubernetes/client-go)**\n\n- `tools/cache/reflector.go`: The `Reflector` struct is the client-side component that calls `ListAndWatch` against the Kubernetes API server. It establishes a watch connection (HTTP chunked transfer or WebSocket), receives `watch.Event` objects, and pushes them into a local `DeltaFIFO` store. The `Reflector` is the entry point for all informer-based controllers in client-go.\n\n**Summary of the full chain:**\n1. A key mutation in etcd triggers `watchableStore` (etcd: `server/mvcc/watchable_store.go`) to generate events.\n2. Events flow through `watchStream` (etcd: `server/mvcc/watcher.go`) — the MVCC-level event channel.\n3. `serverWatchStream` (etcd: `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/watch.go`) serializes events as gRPC `WatchResponse` messages.\n4. The Kubernetes apiserver's `Cacher` (k8s: `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/cacher.go`) receives events via its internal etcd watcher.\n5. `watchCache` (k8s: `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/watch_cache.go`) buffers events in memory.\n6. `cacheWatcher` (k8s: `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/cache_watcher.go`) distributes events to individual watch clients.\n7. The client-side `Reflector` (client-go: `tools/cache/reflector.go`) receives events and updates the local informer store."
